16 2–118.1.
17 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
18 (2) “Fund” means the Maryland Community Investment Venture Fund.
19 (3) “Low– to moderate–income tract” has the meaning stated in § 5–203 of
20 this article.
21 (b) (1) There is a Maryland Community Investment Venture Fund.
22 (2) The Fund is a private venture fund that:
23 (i) Is an instrumentality of the State; and
24 (ii) Uses public and private investment funds.
25 (c) (1) Subject to paragraph (2) of this subsection, the purpose of the Fund is
26 to develop opportunities for banking institutions and credit unions to better serve the needs
27 of low– to moderate–income tracts by:
28 (i) [Investing in] PROMOTING the development of financial
29 product or financial product underwriting innovations that enhance access to capital,

4 SENATE BILL 43
1 funding, and other financial services for CONSUMERS AND businesses in low– to
2 moderate–income tracts in the State THROUGH INVESTMENTS, GRANTS, AND OTHER
3 FORMS OF FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE;
4 (ii) Deploying, testing, and evaluating the innovations for providing
5 capital and funding to CONSUMERS AND businesses in low– to moderate–income tracts in
6 the State; and
7 (iii) Promoting and making the innovations available to banking
8 institutions and credit unions for use in enhancing access to capital, funding, and other
9 financial services for CONSUMERS AND businesses in low– to moderate–income tracts in
10 the State.
11 (2) With the approval of the Commissioner, the purpose of the Fund may
12 be altered in a manner that is consistent with the intent and requirements of this section.
13 (d) (1) (i) The Commissioner shall establish a governance structure for the
14 Fund.
15 (ii) The Commissioner may collaborate with investors in the Fund
16 when establishing the governance structure.
17 (2) The Commissioner, or the Commissioner’s designee, shall serve on the
18 governing body of the Fund.
19 (e) (1) The Commissioner may use up to $250,000 from the Banking
20 Institution and Credit Union Regulation Fund established under § 2–118 of this subtitle to
21 cover the expenses associated with establishing AND ADMINISTERING the Fund, including
22 accounting, advisory, third–party service provider, marketing, and other necessary
23 expenses.
24 (2) To encourage private investment, the Commissioner may provide an
25 [initial] equity capital investment in the Fund in an amount up to $2,500,000 from the
26 Banking Institution and Credit Union Regulation Fund.
27 (f) (1) Through June 30, [2028] 2030, the Commissioner may match an
28 investment made in the Fund by a banking institution or credit union up to the amount of
29 the assessment credit earned by the banking institution or credit union in accordance with
30 § 5–203(d) or § 6–712(c)(4) of this article.
31 (2) The Commissioner may not make an investment in the Fund after June
32 30, [2028] 2030.
33 (g) All investment returns or return of capital from the Fund with respect to an
34 investment authorized by the Commissioner shall be credited to the Banking Institution
35 and Credit Union Regulation Fund.

