13 5–707.
14 (a) (1) In this section, “emergency” has the meaning stated in § 14–307 of the
15 Public Safety Article.
16 (2) “EMERGENCY” INCLUDES A CYBERSECURITY INCIDENT THAT
17 NECESSITATES THE CLOSURE OF A BANKING INSTITUTION OR A BRANCH OF A
18 BANKING INSTITUTION.
19 (b) (1) If the Governor proclaims that an emergency exists in a political
20 subdivision and designates days for the general cessation of business in the subdivision,
21 each banking office that is located within the subdivision shall be closed on those days.
22 (2) If the Governor proclaims that an emergency exists in a political
23 subdivision, the Governor may designate days on which each banking office that is located
24 within the subdivision may be closed.
25 (3) If the Governor proclaims that an emergency exists as to a particular
26 banking office, that office may be closed on those days that the Governor designates.
27 (4) When the Governor authorizes, but does not require, the banking
28 institution to be closed, the chairman of its board of directors or its president shall decide
29 whether to close or remain open.
30 (c) (1) If an emergency exists and affects a banking institution and if it is not
31 practical to obtain a proclamation from the Governor before closing the affected institution,
32 the chairman of its board of directors or its president:

10 SENATE BILL 43
1 (i) May close the banking institution; and
2 (ii) As soon as possible, but within 24 hours after the closing, shall
3 notify the Governor of the reasons for the closing.
4 (2) A banking institution may be closed under this subsection until the
5 earlier of:
6 (i) Issuance by the Governor of a proclamation that relates to the
7 emergency closing;
8 (ii) Notice to the banking institution that the Governor will not issue
9 a proclamation;
10 (iii) Reopening of the banking institution by the chairman of its board
11 of directors or by its president; or
12 (iv) 5 p.m. on the third day after the closing, except for Saturdays,
13 Sundays, and legal holidays.
14 5–806.
